    implementation_delta: |
      Completed LNG-CORE-57: Type system refinement - unified NUMBER type for int/float literals.

      Problem: Parser returns TYPE_INT for integer literals, TYPE_FLOAT for float literals,
      but tests expect TYPE_NUMBER as unified numeric type. This caused 8+ test failures.

      Solution implemented:
      1. Modified runtime/type_contract.py:
         - Changed number literal handling to return TYPE_NUMBER for both int and float
         - Unified type inference: isinstance(value, (int, float)) -> return TYPE_NUMBER
         - Removed separate TYPE_INT/TYPE_FLOAT returns from number literals
         - Preserved runtime behavior: int and float remain distinct at runtime

      2. Updated contracts/SPEC.lnd:
         - Added type_system section with version 1.0.1
         - Documented unified NUMBER type hierarchy
         - Listed all core types: number, bool, string, null, list[T], object, fn, any
         - Documented type inference behavior for number literals
         - Added type checking error documentation

      3. Test results:
         - test_number_literal_is_number: PASS (was FAIL)
         - test_let_binds_value_type_in_body: PASS (was FAIL)
         - 37/38 type contract tests pass
         - 1 pre-existing error in test_call_checks_arity_and_arg_types (call node structure)

      Acceptance criteria status:
      - "check_expr(parse_expr('42')) returns TYPE_NUMBER": VERIFIED
      - "check_expr(parse_expr('3.14')) returns TYPE_NUMBER": VERIFIED
      - All type contract test failures from number literal type: RESOLVED
      - Runtime behavior unchanged: int/float distinct at runtime
      - SPEC updated with type hierarchy documentation: COMPLETE
    tests:
      - runtime/test_type_contract.py: 37/38 pass (1 pre-existing error)
    changed_files:
